{"key":"processedPost-11663000","value":{"id":11663000,"first":11662871,"last":11663046,"when":1261003090,"utime":"12/17/09 12:38 AM","cleanedPost":"Previous advice givers over the years to use a long-term buffer in casing layers neglect to realize one thing: A casing layer is a <i>short term</i> item.&nbsp; A casing layer is rarely in service two months later, and while long term buffers such as ground limestone(calcium carbonate) are fine, they're not required.&nbsp; Using hydrated lime alone works great.&nbsp; Start with about 1 teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peat moss.&nbsp; Give it an hour or two to stabilize and add more if necessary to get the pH to about 8.5 before pasteurization.<br />You'll get a boost by adding up to ten percent gypsum to the casing material.<br />RR"}}